{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}
{{NBA Labour Relations}}
The '''2011 NBA lockout''' was the fourth [[Lockout (industry)|lockout]] in the [[NBA lockout|history]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). The owners began the work stoppage upon expiration of the 2005 [[NBA Collective Bargaining Agreement|collective bargaining agreement]] (CBA). The 161-day lockout began on July 1, 2011 and ended on December 8, 2011. It delayed the start of the {{nbay|2011|app=regular season}} from November 1 to December 25, and it reduced the regular season from 82 to 66 games. The previous [[1998<U+2013>99 NBA lockout|lockout in 1998<U+2013>99]] had shortened the season to 50 games. During the lockout, teams could not [[Trade (sports)|trade]], sign or contact players, and players could not access NBA team facilities, trainers or staffs.

Negotiations between the owners, led by commissioner [[David Stern]], and the players, led by director [[Billy Hunter (American football)|Billy Hunter]] and president [[Derek Fisher]] of the labor union [[National Basketball Players Association]] (NBPA), began in early 2011 and continued through November. The main issues dividing both sides were the division of [[revenue]] and the structure of the [[salary cap]] and [[Luxury tax (sports)|luxury tax]]. Owners proposed to reduce the players<U+2019> share of basketball related income (BRI) from 57% to 47%, but the players countered with 53% of BRI. Owners wanted to implement a hard salary cap and a harsher luxury tax, hoping to increase competition among teams, whereas players wanted to keep the current soft salary cap structure intact.

As both sides failed to reach an agreement, the NBA canceled the preseason and all games through December. On November 14, the players dissolved the union, allowing them to file anti-trust lawsuits against the league. On November 26, both sides reached a tentative agreement to end the lockout. The new CBA calls for a revenue split of 49-to-51.2% and a flexible salary cap structure with harsher luxury tax. After the tentative deal was reached, owners allowed players to have voluntary workouts at team sites starting December 1. After the deal was ratified on December 8, [[training camp]]s, trades and [[free agency]] began the next day. During the lockout, some players signed contracts to play in other countries, mostly in Europe and Asia, with most of them having the option to return upon the lockout's conclusion. The lockout also had a negative impact on the economy due largely to NBA cities losing revenue generated by games as well as television networks losing ratings and advertisement revenue.

==Chronology==
* '''July 1, 2011''':  The lockout begins.<ref name=lockout_begins/>
* '''September 23, 2011''':  The NBA canceled training camp, which was to begin October 3, and the first week of preseason games, which were to run October 9 through 15.<ref name=camp_canceled/>
* '''October 4, 2011''': The NBA canceled the remainder of the preseason.<ref name=abbot_10042011/>
* '''October 10, 2011''': The first two weeks of the regular season canceled.<ref name=stein_10102011/>
* '''October 28, 2011''': All games through November 30 canceled.<ref name="espn-stern-cancel-nov30"/>
* '''November 14, 2011''': The NBPA dissolves [[labor union]] into a [[trade association]].<ref name=union_dissolves/>
* '''November 15, 2011''': The NBA canceled all games through December 15. Players filed [[United States antitrust law|antitrust]] lawsuits against the NBA in California and Minnesota federal courts.<ref name=espn1115/>
* '''November 26, 2011''': The NBA owners and players reached a tentative agreement to end the lockout.<ref name="tentativedeal"/>
* '''December 1, 2011''': The NBPA re-formed as a union.<ref name=union_returns/>
* '''December 8, 2011''': The new CBA is ratified, officially ending the lockout.<ref name="lockoutended">{{cite news |title=Players, owners approve agreement |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7332374/nba-labor-players-owners-vote-ratify-new-labor-agreement |date=December 8, 2011 |accessdate=February 5, 2012 }}</ref>

==Background==
[[File:David Stern.jpg|thumb|160px|upright|right|alt=A man in his 50s with white hair speaks into a microphone. He wears a gray suit, red tie, and glasses.|This was the fourth lockout in [[David Stern]]'s tenure as NBA commissioner.]]
After the [[1998<U+2013>99 NBA lockout|previous lockout]], which shortened the {{nbay|1998|app=season}} from 82 to 50 games, a six-year deal between the owners, led by commissioner [[David Stern]], and the players, led by director [[Billy Hunter (American football)|Billy Hunter]] and president [[Patrick Ewing]] of the labor union [[National Basketball Players Association]] (NBPA), was reached. As the CBA was set to expire on June 30, 2005, the two sides began to negotiate in early 2005. There were several issues obstructing the new agreement, which included adding an [[Eligibility for the NBA Draft|age limit for rookies]], toughening the existing drug-testing program and limiting the length of long-term contracts. However, negotiations went smoothly and the two sides were able to reach a deal in June 2005, avoiding the lockout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/news/CBA_050730.html|title=NBA Collective Bargaining Agreement Ratified and Signed|date=July 30, 2005|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20101202233937/http://www.nba.com/news/CBA_050730.html |archivedate=July 30, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=N.B.A. and Union Can't Agree on Exactly What's at Issue |date=June 16, 2005 |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/16/sports/basketball/16hunter.html |accessdate=August 4, 2011 }}</ref> That deal guaranteed players 57&nbsp;percent of basketball-related income (BRI) and lasted for six years, until June 30, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last=Broussard |first=Chris |title=Sources: Meeting before deadline off |date=October 7, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7072853/meeting-nba-owners-union-scuttled-50-50-split-demand-sources-say |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62H6T0uLv |archivedate=October 8, 2011 }}</ref> A year after signing the deal, eight owners signed a petition requesting Stern address the disparity between [[small-market]] and large-market teams. They wrote that "the hard truth is that our current economic system works only for larger-market teams and a few teams that have extraordinary success ...The rest of us are looking at significant and unacceptable annual financial losses."<ref>{{cite news |last=Windhorst |first=Brian |title=How "small market" owners took control |date=October 25, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/truehoop/post/_/id/32834/how-small-market-owners-took-control |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62if4YMOX |archivedate=October 26, 2011}}</ref>

[[Derek Fisher]] succeeded Ewing as NBPA president in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sandomir |first=Richard |title=Derek Fisher, Champion Point Guard and Face of the Players Union |date=October 18, 2011 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=B18 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/sports/basketball/derek-fisher-champion-point-guard-and-face-of-the-players-union.html?_r=1&sq=derek%20fisher&st=cse&scp=1&pagewanted=all |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62Y0W7KpF |archivedate=October 19, 2011|deadurl=no}}</ref> In early 2011, negotiations on a new CBA began. The league claimed that it was losing $300 million a year (22 out of 30 teams were losing money last season) and proposed to reduce 40% of players' salary (about $800 million) and institute a hard [[NBA salary cap|salary cap]] (at $45 million per team) as opposed to a soft cap (at $58 million) currently in use. The union disputed those figures and steadfastly opposed those changes. Hunter said that he was advising players to prepare for a lockout.<ref>{{cite news |first=Howard |last=Beck |title=Progress of Negotiations Is Hidden in Semantics |date=February 19, 2011 |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/20/sports/basketball/20stern.html |accessdate=August 4, 2011 }}</ref> In May 2011, the NBPA filed a complaint with the [[National Labor Relations Board]] (NLRB), accusing the league of negotiating in bad faith by failing to provide critical financial data to the union and repeatedly threatening to lock out players. The NBA quickly rejected the complaint, saying that the league complies fully with federal labor laws. The union also considered the option of decertification, which allows players to file an antitrust lawsuit against the NBA.<ref>{{cite news |first=Howard |last=Beck |title=Turning to Labor Board, N.B.A. Union Fires First |date=May 24, 2011 |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/25/sports/basketball/players-accuse-nba-of-failing-to-bargain-in-good-faith.html |accessdate=August 4, 2011 }}</ref>

With time winding down, negotiations continued in May and June. On the salary cap, the owners, in their newest proposal, call for a system called the "flex cap" that limits payroll at $62 million but penalizes teams if the teams payroll exceeds the league's average payroll of that season.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gary |last=Washburn |title=NBA owners now offering players <U+2018>flex cap<U+2019> |date=June 22, 2011 |work=Boston Globe |url=http://articles.boston.com/2011-06-22/sports/29690762_1_salary-cap-hard-cap-nba-owners |accessdate=August 4, 2011 }}</ref> The union argued that it is still a hard cap because the ceiling would kick in eventually.<ref>{{cite news |title=NBA players reject 'flex cap' proposal |date=June 21, 2011 |work=CBC.ca |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/basketball/story/2011/06/21/sp-nba-labour.html |accessdate=August 4, 2011 | archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110623064222/http://www.cbc.ca/sports/basketball/story/2011/06/21/sp-nba-labour.html| archivedate= June 23, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> On salary reduction, players offered to cut $500 million over the next five years (their share of BRI would be reduced from 57 to 54.3 percent). The owners instead proposed to cut $2 billion over the next 10 years.<ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Aschburner |title=On eve of deadline, likelihood of compromise looks slim |date=June 29, 2011 |work=NBA.com |url=http://www.nba.com/2011/news/06/29/cba.lockout.deadline/index.html |accessdate=August 4, 2011 }}</ref>

As a last-ditch effort to avert a lockout, owners and players met again on June 30, 2011, to negotiate, but both sides failed to reach a resolution on key issues like salary cap and BRI splits. Both Stern and Hunter said that the two sides remained far apart. The owners demanded a larger share, claiming that they were losing money. The players, on the other hand, were willing to make concessions, but they refused to completely cave in to owners' demands. Negotiations broke off, and the CBA expired at midnight.<ref name="lockoutbegin">{{cite news|last=Cacciola|first=Scott|title=NBA Owners Lock Out Players|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052702304584004576417752764625330.html|work=Sports Journalism|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=July 8, 2011|date=July 1, 2011| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110701015038/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052702304584004576417752764625330.html| archivedate= July 1, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

==Lockout==
===Initial months===
The lockout was officially started by the owners on July 1, 2011, during which, teams could not [[Trade (sports)|trade]], sign or contact players, and players could not access NBA team facilities, trainers or staffs. Negotiations resumed at an August 1 bargaining session, but it fell apart after three hours.<ref name=lockout_begins>{{cite news |title=David Stern, Derek Fisher join talks |date=August 2, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6824510/david-stern-derek-fisher-join-nba-labor-talks-first-time |accessdate=August 4, 2011 }}</ref> On August 2, 2011, the NBA filed two unfair labor practice claims against the NBPA, one at the NLRB and another at a [[List of United States district and territorial courts|federal district court]] in New York. The league accused the players of being uncooperative in negotiations by threatening to dissolve their union and file antitrust lawsuits. Hunter, in a statement released by the union, called the lawsuits "without merit" and that the union would seek to dismiss it in court.<ref>{{cite news |title=NBA files federal lawsuit against players |date=August 3, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6826716/nba-takes-legal-action-locked-players |accessdate=August 4, 2011}}</ref> On August 4, Hunter said that he thought the entire {{nbay|2011|app=season}} would likely be canceled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Billy Hunter doubts entire '11<U+2013>12 season |date=August 4, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6832574/billy-hunter-expects-entire-nba-season-canceled |accessdate=August 4, 2011}}</ref>

[[File:Derek Fisher.jpg|thumb|160px |right|[[Derek Fisher]] was the [[National Basketball Players Association|players union]] president during the lockout.]]
The NBPA and the owners returned to negotiate again on August 31 with a sense of urgency. No specifics were disclosed although both sides hoped to meet again soon. "Everyone loses if we don't reach an agreement, that's something that I think has always been understood," said union president [[Derek Fisher]]. "I will say we are not apart in terms of an agreed urgency on getting a deal done," said NBA deputy commissioner [[Adam Silver]].<ref>{{cite news |title=NBA owners, union meet for 6 hours |date=September 1, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6914421/nba-lockout-nbpa-owners-meet-six-hours-manhattan |accessdate=September 1, 2011}}</ref>

The union and owners met again on September 13 but the negotiation soon collapsed. The salary cap structure remained the main source of disagreement. Owners wanted to create a hard cap for team payroll. The union wanted to keep the current structure intact, referring to it as a "blood issue". Players were willing to cut salary only if owners agree to compromise on the salary cap. But owners were unwilling to concede, saying that there must be a system in place that allows all teams to compete.<ref>{{cite news |title=No progress made after latest labor talk |date=September 13, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6965103/nba-players-union-impasse-time-start-season-now-doubt |accessdate=September 14, 2011}}</ref> Five of the [[sports agent]]s<U+2014>[[Arn Tellem]], [[Bill Duffy (basketball)|Bill Duffy]], [[Mark Bartelstein]], [[Jeff Schwartz]] and [[Dan Fegan]]<U+2014>who represent one-third of NBA players spoke with each other about [[decertification|decertifying]] the union. They believed owners have most of the leverage in negotiation and viewed decertification as a way for players to take control. Hunter said however that players have not considered decertification at this point.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sources: Agents want union to decertify |date=September 14, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6967636/nba-player-agents-angling-get-players-union-decertify |accessdate=September 14, 2011 |first=Chris |last=Broussard |coauthor=Abbott, Henry}}</ref>

On September 15, Fisher sent an email to 400-plus players asking for unity. In the email, he said that recent meetings were "effective". He suggested that the failure of having a deal was not due to disagreement between players and owners, but due to disagreement among owners. Fisher also used the opportunity to counter agents' suggestion of disbanding the union, saying that they were not making "a drastic move that leaves players without a union". According to sources, there was indeed disagreement among the owners. Some thought players' proposal of taking 52% of BRI was fair, and were willing to compromise on things like tying players' future earnings to NBA's future revenue growth and maintaining current salary level. [[Cleveland Cavaliers|Cavaliers]]' [[Dan Gilbert (businessman)|Dan Gilbert]] and [[Phoenix Suns|Suns']] [[Robert Sarver]] were among the hardliners who oppose the deal while [[New York Knicks|Knicks']] [[James L. Dolan|James Dolan]] and the Lakers' [[Jerry Buss]] were among the group in favor of it.<ref>{{cite news |title=Derek Fisher: Rift among owners |date=September 15, 2011 |work=ESPN LA.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/nba/story/_/id/6973675/nba-lockout-derek-fisher-los-angeles-lakers-emails-players-says-owners-rift |accessdate=September 15, 2011 |first=Dave |last=McMenamin}}</ref> Stern denied that there was a rift among owners the following day, saying, "I don't know what the basis of Derek's belief is."<ref>{{cite news |title=Players, then owners declare unity |date=September 16, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6975352/nba-lockout-players-owners-declare-unity-separate-meetings |accessdate=September 16, 2011 |first=Dave |last=McMenamin |coauthor=MacMahon, Tim }}</ref>

===Cancellations===
On September 23, 2011, the NBA canceled training camp, which was to begin October 3, and the first week of preseason games, which were to run October 9 through 15.<ref name=camp_canceled>[http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7008269/nba-postpones-camps-cancels-43-preseason-games NBA postpones camps indefinitely]. ''ESPN.com''. Retrieved September 23, 2011.</ref> The incident marks only the second time in league history that games have been lost to a labor stoppage. Both the owners and the union had planned to meet on September 30 in New York and pledged to continue through the weekends if progress was being made. A source close to the situation leaked to [[ESPN]] that Stern plans to threaten the cancellation of the season if no deal is made, but the union sees this as a scare tactic and not a serious threat.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Stern: Season hangs in balance |date=September 28, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7031637/nba-lockout-owners-players-meet-friday-possibly-weekend |accessdate=September 28, 2011 |first=Marc |last=Stein }}</ref> Commentators speculated that Stern wants to put pressure on the players and prevent negotiation from dragging through the fall.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Stern's scary talk |date=September 28, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/truehoop/post/_/id/32128/david-sterns-scary-talk |accessdate=September 28, 2011 |first=Henry |last=Abbott }}</ref> The meeting on September 30 was tense as [[Dwyane Wade]] reportedly yelled at Stern after he pointed his finger at Wade. The players nearly stormed out, but they remained in the meeting only after Hunter asked them to. Stern also backed down from his earlier threat that he would cancel the season if there is no deal.<ref>{{cite news |title=NBA-union talks to continue Saturday |date=October 1, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7039251/nba-labor-talks-players-owners-return-talks-saturday-tense-moments |accessdate=October 1, 2011 }}</ref>

[[File:Jerry Buss playing the WSOP.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Owner [[Jerry Buss]] was open to sharing a larger share of revenues with players.]]
On October 4, the NBA canceled the remainder of the preseason. Stern said the league would lose $200 million by canceling the preseason, and warned that the first two weeks of the season would be in jeopardy if no deal is reached by October 10. The players proposed that they receive 53% of BRI, while the owners countered with 47%. The two sides then discussed a 50<U+2013>50 split of BRI, with the owners offering the players 49% of BRI with incentives that would raise the value to 51%. The players countered by asking for 51%, which would increase to 53 percent using those same incentives. It was rejected by the owners.<ref name=abbot_10042011>{{cite news |last1=Abbott |first1=Henry |last2=Broussard |first2=Chris |title=NBA to cancel games if no deal Monday |date=October 4, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7059973/nba-labor-first-two-weeks-season-canceled-no-deal-monday-david-stern-says |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62CLrPquj |archivedate=October 4, 2011}}</ref> Attempts for the sides to meet on October 7 failed. The union said the NBA demanded a 50<U+2013>50 revenue split prior to the meeting, while the league refuted making any such demands.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sources: NBA, union meeting Sunday |date=October 9, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7080905/nba-lockout-sides-meet-11th-hour-attempt-sources-say |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62JxJ6fse |archivedate=October 9, 2011}}</ref> After talks on October 9 and 10, the two sides were unable to reach a deal and Stern subsequently canceled the first two weeks of regular-season games, which were originally scheduled to begin on November 1.<ref name=stein_10102011>{{cite news |author=Stein |first=Marc |title=NBA cancels first 2 weeks of season |date=October 10, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7085089/nba-labor-david-stern-cancels-first-two-weeks-nba-season |accessdate=October 10, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=NBA labor talks resume in New York |date=October 10, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7083100/no-nba-labor-deal-headed-deadline-day |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62LTycHUo |archivedate=October 11, 2011}}</ref>  BRI remained the main issue, but other differences included [[Luxury tax (sports)|luxury tax]], player contract length, and the [[mid-level exception]]. The owners proposed a $2 tax for every $1 that a team spends above the tax threshold for player salaries. The tax would rise to as high as $4 for every $1 above the limit for teams that are repeat offenders. The previous CBA in comparison called for a $1 tax for every $1 over the limit.<ref name=stein_10102011/> The players refused to accept a hard salary cap, which they felt the more punitive luxury taxes would effectively create.<ref>{{cite news |title=NBA postpones board meetings, talks with union, mediator |agency=Associate Press |date=October 19, 2011 |work=NBA.com |publisher=NBA Media Ventures |url=http://www.nba.com/2011/news/10/19/labor-talks.ap/ |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62Ykv9n2j |archivedate=October 19, 2011}}</ref> Stern said the owners felt a harsher luxury tax would make the league more competitive. Wade countered that a small-market team like the [[San Antonio Spurs]] had won [[List of NBA champions|multiple championships]].<ref name=adande_10162011>{{cite news |last1=Adande |first1=J.A. |last2=McMenamin |first2=Dave |title=NBPA stresses unity in player meeting |date=October 16, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7102787/nba-lockout-nbpa-leaders-meet-players-stress-unity |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62XmmQFC8 |archivedate=October 19, 2011}}</ref> [[Andrew Zimbalist]], an economist at [[Smith College]], said that "the statistical correlation between payroll and win percentage is practically nonexistent" in the NBA.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=Owners Sacrificing Games (or Season?) in Bid to Balance N.B.A. |date=October 12, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=A1 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/12/sports/basketball/owners-and-players-divided-by-push-to-restructure-the-nba.html?pagewanted=all |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62sgubf4e |archivedate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> ''[[ESPN.com]]'' concluded that a team's [[NBA draft|draft]] efficiency accounted for 34% of its [[winning percentage]] in the past decade, while payroll showed only a 7% correlation.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haberstroh |first=Tim |title=The payroll and competitive balance myth |date=October 26, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/truehoop/post/_/id/32841/the-payroll-and-competitive-balance-myth |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62shNzLFv |archivedate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' noted that a fairer system was needed for the small-market teams, but the league's popularity historically relied on predictably successful teams with multiple superstars.<ref>{{cite news |last=Araton |first=Harvey |title=Parity, Great for N.F.L., May Hurt N.B.A. |date=November 27, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=SP1 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/27/sports/basketball/new-deal-helps-nbas-small-market-teams.html?_r=1&ref=basketball |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63Xp3FlEd |archivedate=November 28, 2011}}</ref>

NBPA leaders met with around 30&nbsp;players on October 14 and stressed unity.  [[Washington Wizards]] player [[JaVale McGee]] left the meeting early and told reporters there were some players "saying that they're ready to fold", but the majority was united.<ref name=adande_10162011/> McGee later denied mentioning that players were ready to fold, but his comment was recorded by reporters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dahlberg |first=Tim | title=Time for players to step up in NBA lockout |date=October 17, 2011 |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]] |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2011/10/17/sports/s161355D75.DTL |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62Xqmq2hn |archivedate=October 19, 2011}}</ref> Fisher said McGee had "no ability to make that statement" based on the limited time he spent at the meeting.<ref name=adande_10162011/>

Owners and players met again on October 18<U+2013>20 for 30 hours of talks over three days.<ref name=nba_talks_break>{{cite news |title=NBA talks break off, none planned |date=October 21, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7127448/nba-lockout-talks-break-early-thursday-planned |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62canjPGX |archivedate=October 22, 2011}}</ref>  They met before a federal mediator, [[George H. Cohen|George Cohen]]<U+2014>the director of the [[Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service (United States)|Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service]]. Cohen tried unsuccessfully to resolve the [[2011 NFL lockout]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Greenhouse |first=Steven |title=Mediator in N.B.A. Talks Has Strong Sports Pedigree |date=October 20, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=B12 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/20/sports/basketball/george-cohen-nba-mediator-has-experience-for-role.html?_r=1&sq=george%20cohen&st=cse&scp=1&pagewanted=all |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62caxeRgP |archivedate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> At the conclusion of the meetings, the sides remained split on the revenue split and the structure of the salary cap.  The league proposed a 50<U+2013>50 split of BRI, and the players proposed a range that would allow them as low as 50% of BRI to a maximum of 53%, depending on the league's revenues.<ref name=nba_talks_break/> Gilbert told the players to trust that the salary cap issues could be resolved if they accepted the 50<U+2013>50 proposal. Hunter responded, "I can't trust your gut. I got to trust my own gut."<ref name=lee>{{cite news |last=Lee |first=Michael |title=NBA labor negotiations hit another snag |date=October 21, 2011 |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wizards-insider/post/nba-labor-negotiations-hit-another-snag/2011/10/21/gIQAOtnN2L_blog.html |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62cb9ftDB |archivedate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> Silver and [[San Antonio Spurs]] owner [[Peter Holt]] told reporters that the players refused to negotiate after the 50<U+2013>50 proposal. Fisher told the press "that you guys were lied to" by the owners.<ref name=lee/> Hunter said the owners told them, "Take it or leave it."<ref name=lee/> Cohen decided that there was "no useful purpose" to continue mediation.<ref name=lee/> Tentative agreements were reached on smaller issues, allowing a one-time exemption for teams to waive players without counting against the salary cap, granting teams an annual exemption to waive players and prorate the impact to the salary cap over multiple years, and a mid-level exception of $5 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=With Talks at a Halt, Silence Reigns |date=October 22, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=D4 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/22/sports/basketball/with-nba-talks-halted-sides-predict-a-meeting-next-week.html?scp=3&sq=george%20cohen&st=cse |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62cbHyXWM |archivedate=October 22, 2011}}</ref>

Hunter characterized the small-market owners as being inflexible in negotiation. However, ''The New York Times'' wrote that the views of individual owners "cannot be easily categorized by market size, revenue, personal wealth or championship aspirations."<ref name=beck_10252011>{{cite news |last1=Beck |first1=Howard |last2=Belson |first2=Ken |title=N.B.A. Owners<U+2019> Mutual Dependence Outweighs Divisions |date=October 25, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=B14 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/25/sports/basketball/nba-owners-are-not-unified-in-all-their-interests.html?ref=basketball&pagewanted=all |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62ibLrbqp |archivedate=October 26, 2011}}</ref> [[Dallas Mavericks]] owner [[Mark Cuban]], whose team is in the fifth-largest market and has one of the highest payrolls, and [[Portland Trail Blazers]] owner [[Paul Allen]], the 23rd-wealthiest person in America, are as interested as small-market owners in changing the economy of the NBA in an effort to increase competition. While owners of profitable teams like Buss and Dolan are willing to accept modest changes to the CBA, they remain united with the small-market teams based on concerns for the league's long-term health.<ref name=beck_10252011/>

Despite the earlier cancellation announcement, the players and the league hoped that a full 82-game schedule could be salvaged if a deal is reached in time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Abbot |first=Henry |title=82 games may be too many |date=October 27, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/truehoop/post/_/id/32871/82-games-may-be-too-many |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62n3PdNBh |archivedate=October 29, 2011}}</ref> On October 28, Stern announced the cancellation of all games through November 30 after negotiations regarding division of revenue ended without an agreement. He said that Hunter was unwilling "to go a penny below 52%" on BRI, while Hunter said, "We made a lot of concessions, but unfortunately at this time it's not enough."<ref name="espn-stern-cancel-nov30">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7153136/nba-lockout-david-stern-announces-more-game-cancellations|title=NBA games canceled through Nov. 30|publisher=''ESPN.com'' (ESPN Internet Ventures)|date=October 28, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62n3RhyUc|archivedate=October 29, 2011}}</ref> Stern indicated that an 82-game season was no longer possible. He added that tentative agreement was reached for maximum contract lengths of five years for players staying with their teams or four years when signing with another team.<ref name="espn-stern-cancel-nov30"/>

[[File:Michael Jordan.jpg|thumb|right|160px|Owner [[Michael Jordan]], a former player, was among the hardline owners during negotiations.]]
Reports of division among players and owners surfaced. [[Jason Whitlock]] of ''[[Foxsports.com]]'' wrote that Fisher was privately working with Stern on the 50<U+2013>50 split and that Hunter confronted Fisher about the issue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Whitlock |first=Jason |title=Is Fisher in Stern's back pocket? |date=October 29, 2011 |work=FoxSports.com |publisher=Fox Sports Interactive Media |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nba/story/Whitlock-NBA-lockout-David-Stern-has-Derek-Fisher-in-back-pocket-Billy-Hunter-players-union-not-pleased-102811 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62sYVgFbU |archivedate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> Fisher and Stern denied a private meeting took place.<ref name=beck_11022011/> In a letter to the players, Fisher called the reports "absurd" and demanded "a retraction for the libelous and defamatory stories" through his attorneys.<ref name=beck_11022011>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=Fisher Fights Back Against Reports |date=November 2, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=http://offthedribble.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/02/fisher-fights-back-against-reports/ |accessdate=November 2, 2011}}</ref><ref name=stein_11012011/> Hunter said his "relationship with Derek is very good. There was no confrontation."<ref name=stein_11012011>{{cite news |last=Stein |first=Marc |title=Derek Fisher defends loyalty in letter |date=November 1, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7176180/nba-lockout-derek-fisher-says-report-questioning-union-loyalty-absurd |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62sYqVeXy |archivedate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Whitlock |first=Jason |title=Fisher in denial over labor rift |date=November 1, 2011 |work=FoxSports.com |publisher=Fox Sports Interactive Media |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nba/story/derek-fisher-los-angeles-lakers-in-denial-over-nba-labor-rift-jason-whitlock-110111 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62sZ9aXvl |archivedate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> Fisher, as union president, is not empowered to make unilateral decisions for the union. While Fisher believed a 50<U+2013>50 deal could be considered, Hunter maintained that the owners should never "make the same or more than the players."<ref name=beck_11042011>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=50 N.B.A. Players Considering Dissolution of Union |date=November 4, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times | page=B10 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/04/sports/basketball/nba-talks-to-resume-saturday.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62x8AFp8T |archivedate=November 4, 2011}}</ref> [[Miami Heat]] owner [[Micky Arison]], one of the owners willing to settle with players,<ref name=beck_10252011/> responded to a fan complaining about greedy owners and players on [[Twitter]], saying that "You are barking at the wrong owner." He was fined $500,000 by Stern, five times larger than any previous amount against an owner for publicly commenting on the lockout.<ref>{{cite news |last=Windhorst |first=Brian |title=NBA fines Heat owner Micky Arison |date=November 1, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/truehoop/miamiheat/story/_/id/7175679/nba-lockout-miami-heat-owner-micky-arison-fined-500000-twitter-comments-labor-talks-sources-say |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62saUAzQj |archivedate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> A group of 10 to 14 hardline owners want to cap the players' share of BRI at 50% and as low as 47. The group is led by [[Charlotte Bobcats]] owner [[Michael Jordan]]. During the labor dispute in 1998, then-player Jordan told [[Washington Wizards]] then-owner [[Abe Pollin]], "If you can<U+2019>t make a profit, you should sell your team."<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=Hard-Line Factions Threaten Latest N.B.A. Negotiations |date=November 5, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=D7 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/05/sports/basketball/hard-line-factions-threaten-latest-nba-negotiations.html?ref=basketball |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/630p6jgPe |archivedate=November 7, 2011}}</ref> Whitlock called Jordan a "sellout" wanting "current players to pay for his incompetence."<ref name=whitlock_11052011>{{cite news |last=Whitlock |first=Jason |title=MJ sells out players with hard-line stance |date=November 5, 2011 |work=FoxSports.com |publisher=Fox Sports Interactive Media |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nba/story/Michael-Jordan-siding-with-David-Stern-in-NBA-lockout-a-selfish-betrayal-110411 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/630qCZe0Z |archivedate=November 7, 2011}}</ref> He cited Jordan's executive decisions to draft disappointing players [[Kwame Brown]] and [[Adam Morrison]].<ref name=whitlock_11052011/>

In early November, about 50 players renewed talks of union decertification if the union went lower than 52.5% of BRI or agreed to additional restrictions on contracts, salary-cap exceptions, or free agency. Decertifying would require that 30% of the union<U+2014>about 130 players<U+2014>sign a petition, allowing an election under the auspices of the NLRB by all NBPA members to decertify with a [[majority|simple majority]]. The NLRB traditionally does not consider a decertification petition while a charge is pending, such as the NBPA's unfair labor practice charges filed in August.<ref name=beck_11042011/>

The owners and players union met on November 6, and they were joined again by federal mediator Cohen. The players proposed that they receive 51% of BRI, with a 1% portion taken out for retired players. The owners offered a "band" that would pay the players 49 to 51%, depending on revenue growth. [[Jeffrey L. Kessler|Jeff Kessler]], the union<U+2019>s attorney, said the league's proposal was really 50.2% and called the possibility of reaching 51% an "illusion."<ref>{{cite news |title=Deal on table until Wednesday |date=November 6, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7195620/nba-owners-players-end-talks-deal-table-wednesday |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/630nFmLOG |archivedate=November 7, 2011}}</ref> The league also proposed restrictions for teams that pay the luxury tax, banning them from [[sign and trade]] deals and limiting their use of the mid-level exception. They also proposed a "repeater tax" for teams that exceed the tax threshold thrice in a five-year span. Stern issued an ultimatum, giving the players until November 9 to accept the deal before it is lowered to 47% BRI and a flex salary cap.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=N.B.A. Owners Give Players 4 Days to Accept Final Offer |date=November 6, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=SP5 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/06/sports/basketball/nba-lockout-talks-with-mediator.html?ref=basketball&pagewanted=all |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/630nPTUyy |archivedate=November 7, 2011}}</ref>

On November 15, the NBA canceled all games through December 15.<ref name=espn1115>[http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7239168/source-nba-cancels-games-dec-15 Source: NBA cancels games through Dec. 13; players file 2 antitrust suits v. NBA]. ''ESPN.com''. Retrieved November 15, 2011.</ref>

===Dissolving the union===
The union rejected the offer on November 9 and asked for another bargaining session.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stein |first=Marc |title=Union rejects owners' latest offer |date=November 9, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7209093/nba-lockout-players-reject-david-stern-ultimatum-offer-want-further-talks }}</ref> The two sides met again as the deadline passed. After two days of negotiation, the owners put forth a revised final offer and said that they were done bargaining. If accepted by the players, Stern hoped to start a 72-game season in mid December.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=A Final Proposal, With Hopes of a Vote |date=November 10, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/11/sports/basketball/imminent-deal-in-nba-no-but-sides-keep-negotiating.html?ref=basketball }}</ref> On November 14, the union rejected the last offer and dissolved the union.<ref name=union_dissolves>{{cite news |title=NBA players reject owners' offer |date=November 14, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7234180/nba-lockout-players-not-accept-deal-seek-decertify-billy-hunter-says }}</ref> The NBPA was converted into a [[trade association]], enabling the players as individual employees to participate in a class action antitrust lawsuit against the league, calling the lockout an illegal group [[boycott]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Newcomb |first=Tim |title=NBA Players Look to Disband Union: Will There Be a Season At All? |date=November 15, 2011 |magazine=TIME |url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2011/11/15/nba-players-look-to-disband-union-will-there-be-a-season-at-all/ |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63DrzVjuP |archivedate=November 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=N.B.A. Season in Peril as Players Reject Offer |date=November 15, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=A1 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/15/sports/basketball/players-reject-nbas-offer-and-begin-to-disband-union.html?ref=sports&pagewanted=all |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63Dv730qY |archivedate=November 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Hunter |first=G. William |coauthors=Fisher, Derek; The NBPA Executive Committee |title=NBPA disclaimer |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://assets.espn.go.com/pdf/2011/1114/NBPA_toAllPlayers.pdf |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63DvLUrbX |archivedate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> Attorney [[David Boies]], who represented the NFL owners in their 2011 lockout, agreed to represent the players and join Keesler, who also represented the players in the NFL lockout.<ref>{{cite news |last=Belson |first=Ken |title=Lawyer for N.F.L. in Lockout Joins Players in N.B.A. Fight |date=November 14, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/15/sports/basketball/lawyer-for-nfl-in-lockout-joins-players-in-nba-fight.html?ref=basketball |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63Cc6m6mz |archivedate=November 14, 2011}}</ref> On November 15, one group of NBA players (including [[Carmelo Anthony]], [[Chauncey Billups]], [[Kawhi Leonard]], and [[Leon Powe]]) filed an antitrust lawsuit against the NBA in a California federal court, while another (including [[Anthony Tolliver]], [[Ben Gordon (basketball)|Ben Gordon]], [[Caron Butler]] and [[Derrick Williams (basketball)|Derrick Williams]]) filed their own suit against the NBA in a Minnesota federal court.<ref name=espn1115/> November 15 was also the day players were to receive their first paychecks if the season was played.<ref name="paychecks"/>

On November 21, the California lawsuit was dropped in order to merge with the Minnesota lawsuit. Boies hoped that the move would speed up the process since the courts will likely merge the suits as they are similar complaints seeking the same outcome. The league has until December 5 to respond in court.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=N.B.A. Players Merge Lawsuits; No Hearing Date Set |date=November 21, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/22/sports/basketball/nba-players-merge-lawsuits.html |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63T6Cx9Bm |archivedate=November 21, 2011}}</ref>

===Settlement===
[[Image:Derrick Rose 02.jpg|thumb|left|In a rule named after [[Derrick Rose]], accomplished players coming off their rookie contract could earn more money in the new CBA.]]
On November 23, the league and the players agreed to resume negotiating on November 25.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=N.B.A. and Players Resume Negotiating, With Christmas Day in Their Sights |date=November 23, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/24/sports/basketball/nba-and-players-resume-negotiating.html?_r=1 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63T6f1PjK |archivedate=November 23, 2011}}</ref> On November 26, after 15 hours of talks, a tentative deal was reached.<ref name="tentativedeal">{{cite news |title=Tentative NBA deal reached |date=November 26, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7281052/nba-owners-players-get-tentative-deal |accessdate=November 26, 2011 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/649ZGxBdk |archivedate=December 23, 2011 }}</ref> The NBPA re-formed as a union on December 1, receiving support from over 300 players, exceeding the requirement for at least 260 signatures.<ref name=union_returns>{{cite news |title=NBA players authorize return of union |date=December 1, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |agency=Associated Press |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7304086/nba-players-authorize-return-players-union-according-nbpa |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63cZa8W6N |archivedate=December 1, 2011}}</ref> Signature cards were sent to the roughly 440&nbsp;players on rosters at the end of the previous season, as well as to the [[2011 NBA Draft|60&nbsp;rookies drafted in 2011]] and to players who signed at least two 10-day contracts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=N.B.A. Players Union Set to Resume Business |date=December 2, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=B14 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/02/sports/basketball/nba-players-will-re-form-union.html?_r=1&ref=basketball |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63fXiJEtw |archivedate=December 3, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Aldridge |first=David |title=Players begin process of re-forming their union |date=November 29, 2011 |work=NBA.com |publisher=NBA Media Ventures |url=http://www.nba.com/2011/news/11/29/union-cards/index.html |accessdate=December 4, 2011}}</ref> The re-formation enabled further negotiations with the league on secondary issues such as the age limit for the NBA draft and rules on players being sent to and recalled from the [[NBA D-League]].<ref name=stein_11272011/> The players and owners concluded their voting on the deal on December 8,<ref>{{cite news |last=Broussard |first=Chris |title=Players prepare to vote on CBA |date=December 7, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7326259/nba-players-prepare-vote-new-cba |accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref> when the deal was ratified, and the lockout ended after 161 days. The owners approved the deal by a 25<U+2013>5 vote, while 86% of the more than 200 players who voted approved the deal.<ref name="lockoutended"/> Miami Heat's Micky Arison and Dallas Mavericks' Mark Cuban are the two owners who have publicly disclosed that they voted against the new CBA.<ref>{{cite news |title=Micky Arison voted against new CBA |date=December 22, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/truehoop/miamiheat/story/_/id/7380869/miami-heat-owner-micky-arison-cast-protest-vote-new-cba |accessdate=December 23, 2011 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/649ZQjksM |archivedate=December 23, 2011 }}</ref>

The players would receive 51.2% of BRI in 2011<U+2013>12, with a 49-to-51 band in subsequent years.<ref name=stein_11272011>{{cite news |last=Stein |first=Marc |title=Billy Hunter sends players memo on BRI |date=November 27, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7285446/billy-hunter-tells-players-get-512-percent-bri-2011-12 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63Zu2UMw1 |archivedate=November 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=coon_11282011>{{cite news |last=Coon |first=Larry |authorlink=Larry Coon |title=Breaking down changes in new CBA |date=November 28, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/page/CBA-111128/how-new-nba-deal-compares-last-one |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63ZuFTeEO |archivedate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> Teams are allowed a one-time amnesty exemption to waive one player and remove him from the team's salary cap. The player could be claimed off waivers by the highest bidder; the waiving team would be responsible for the remaining salary without it counting against their cap.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=Poof! Goes a Bad Contract, if Any N.B.A. Team Wishes |date=November 28, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=D1 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/28/sports/basketball/each-nba-team-can-waive-one-bad-contract.html?_r=1&ref=basketball |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63av9T3Ph |archivedate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> In a rule dubbed the "Derrick Rose Rule" after the [[Derrick Rose|2011 NBA Most Valuable Player Award winner]], a player finishing his rookie contract could be re-signed at up to 30% of his team's salary cap<U+2014>an increase from the previous CBA's 25%<U+2014>if he was either a two-time [[NBA All-Star Game|All-Star]] starter, twice voted [[All-NBA Team]], or won an [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award|MVP award]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Derrick Rose eager for season to start |date=November 29, 2011 |work=ESPNChicago.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/nba/story/_/id/7294815/chicago-bulls-derrick-rose-surprised-derrick-rose-rule |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63cOM7CcK |archivedate=December 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Aschburner |first=Steve |title=New CBA spreads gains, pains to both sides |date=November 26, 2011 |work=NBA.com |publisher=NBA Media Ventures |url=http://www.nba.com/2011/news/features/steve_aschburner/11/26/cba-deal/index.html |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63cQeT3iz |archivedate=December 1, 2011}}</ref> The maximum salary for a player otherwise would remain unchanged at 25, 30, or 35% of the salary cap, depending on the player's years of service.<ref name=coon_11282011/>

