! scope="col" colspan="3"|Collective Bargaining Agreement comparisons<ref name=coon_11282011/>
|-
! scope="col" style="width:80px"| Characteristic
! scope="col" style="width:200px"| 2005
! scope="col" style="width:250px"| 2011
|-
! scope="row" | Length of agreement
| 7 years, with league opt-out option in 2011
| 10 years, with opt-out in 2017 by either side
|-
! scope="row" | Revenue split
|<u>''Players''</u>: 57%
<u>''Owners''</u>: 43%
|<u>''Players''</u>: 49<U+2013>51%
<u>''Owners''</u>: 49<U+2013>51%
|-
!scope="row" |Minimum team salary
| 75% of salary cap
| 85<U+2013>90%
|-
!scope="row" |Luxury tax
|$1 for every $1 above the luxury-tax threshold
|Incrementally increase from 1:1 for every $5 million above the threshold
|-
!scope="row" |Limits on tax-paying teams
|None
|Smaller midlevel exception, limits on salary acquired in a trade, and no [[bi-annual exception]].
|-
!scope="row"|Maximum new contract length
|<u>''[[Larry Bird exception]]''</u>: 6 years with 10.5 percent raises for Bird free agents<BR>
<u>''Others''</u>: 5 years with 8 percent raises.
|<u>''Larry Bird exception''</u>: 5 years with 7.5 percent raises<BR>
<u>''Others''</u>: 4 years with 4.5 percent raises
|-
!scope="row" |Max contract extension length
|<u>''Rookies''</u>: 5 years<BR>
<u>''Others''</u>: 5 years, which includes years remaining on existing contract
|<u>''Rookies''</u>: 4 years, with each team allowed one designated player at 5 years for maximum salary<BR>
<u>''Others''</u>: 4 years, which includes years remaining on existing contract
|-
!scope="row" |Maximum contract salary
|Approximately 25, 30 or 35&nbsp;percent of the salary cap, depending on the player's years of service.
|Same as 2005, but some players coming off their rookie contract qualify for the 30 percent maximum if they meet certain criteria.
|-
!scope="row" |Midlevel exception
|Five years starting at the average salary ($5.765 million in 2010<U+2013>11), with 8 percent raises.
|<u>''Non-tax paying teams''</u>: Four years starting at $5 million (base salary grows by 3 percent annually beginning in 2013<U+2013>14), with 4.5 percent raises.<BR>
<u>''Tax paying teams''</u>: Three years, a $3 million base salary (which grows by 3 percent annually beginning in 2013<U+2013>14) and 4.5 percent raises.<BR>
<u>''Teams with cap room''</u>: Previously had no midlevel exception. Now receive a new exception that is for two years and starts at $2.5 million (growing 3 percent annually).
|-
!scope="row" |Trades
|Teams over the cap can acquire a maximum of 125 percent plus $100,000 of the salaries they trade away. A team can receive a maximum of $3 million cash per trade.
|<u>''Tax paying teams''</u>: Same as 2005. Starting in 2013<U+2013>14, teams exceeding the tax threshold by more than $4 million cannot receive a player in a sign-and-trade transaction.<BR>
<u>''Non-tax paying teams''</u>: Can acquire up to the lesser of 150 percent plus $100,000, or 100 percent plus $5 million of the salaries they trade away. The maximum cash a team can pays or receive in trade is $3 million annually.
|-
!scope="row" |Escrow
|8 percent (in 2010<U+2013>11) withheld to ensure players receive the correct revenue split. If [[escrow]] withholding is insufficient, the following season's salaries are reduced to compensate.
|10 percent withheld annually. If the withholding is insufficient, the difference is deducted from the players' retirement benefits and not the following season's salary.
|-
!scope="row" |Amnesty
|One player can be waived prior to the start of the 2005<U+2013>06 season. The salary of the waived player does not count toward the luxury tax.
|One player can be waived prior to the start of any season, but only once during the agreement. Only players signed under the 2005 CBA are eligible. The salary of the waived player will not count toward the salary cap or luxury tax.
|}
{{clear}}

===Racial comments===
[[File:Bryant Gumbel cropped.jpg|thumb|right|120px|Journalist [[Bryant Gumbel]] evoked slavery in his lockout editorial.]]
[[Bryant Gumbel]] on his [[HBO]] ''[[Real Sports]]'' show in October likened Stern's role in the lockout to a "modern [[Plantation#Slavery, para-slavery and plantations|plantation]] overseer, treating NBA men as if they were his boys ... keeping the hired hands in their place."<ref>{{cite news |last=Golliver |first=Ben |title=Bryant Gumbel evokes slavery in David Stern rant |date=October 19, 2011 |work=CBSSports.com |publisher=CBS Interactive |url=http://eye-on-basketball.blogs.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/22748484/32813465 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/636Ua9fq1 |archivedate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> The NBA owners are predominantly [[White American|white]], while the players are mostly [[African American|black]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Tour<U+00E9> |title=For the Love of God, Stop Calling Pro Athletes <U+2018>Slaves<U+2019> |date=November 3, 2011 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |url=http://ideas.time.com/2011/11/03/stop-calling-professional-athletes-slaves/ |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/636UQAjLv |archivedate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> ESPN noted that [[William C. Rhoden]] in his book ''$40 Million Slaves'' had earlier dealt with the topic of players as "[[Slavery in the United States|slaves]]" in spite of earning millions of dollars.<ref>{{cite news |last=Abbott |first=Henry |title=David Stern and the plantation |date=November 10, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/truehoop/post/_/id/32634/david-stern-and-the-plantation |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/636Ui1Sux |archivedate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Stern dismissed Gumbel's comments as "an occupational hazard" of being the NBA commissioner.<ref>{{cite news |last=Young |first=Royce |title=Stern on Gumbel: 'It's an occupational hazard' |date=November 8, 2011 |work=CBSSports.com |publisher=CBS Interactive |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/22748484/33194578 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/636UopDiG |archivedate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> In early November, Kessler criticized the owners' "take it or leave it" bargaining approach: "instead of treating the players like partners, they<U+2019>re treating them like plantation workers."<ref>{{cite news |last=Golliver |first=Ben |title=Kessler: NBPA treated 'like plantation workers |date=November 8, 2011 |work=CBSSports.com |publisher=CBS Interactive |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/22748484/33199068 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/636V0pHxz |archivedate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> Hall of Famer [[Magic Johnson]] called the comments "ridiculous" and defended Stern's record of promoting blacks.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mahoney |first=Brian |title=Magic Johnson defends David Stern, dismisses claims of racism |date=November 9, 2011 |newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]] |agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.freep.com/article/20111109/SPORTS03/111109061/Magic-Johnson-defends-David-Stern-dismisses-claims-racism |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/636VAiQ5l |archivedate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> ''[[ESPN The Magazine]]'' said that the NBPA did not condone Kessler's statements, and they had intentionally avoided getting involved with Gumbel's earlier remarks. Kessler later apologized for his comments.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jeffrey Kessler apologizes for remark |date=November 9, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7211447/nba-lockout-jeffrey-kessler-apologizes-plantation-workers-comment |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/636VJMJlF |archivedate=November 10, 2011}}</ref>

===Impact===
The [[#Rescheduled season|revised season schedule]] with 16 fewer regular-season games and a reduced preseason lost the owners and players an estimated $400 million each.<ref>{{cite news|last=Beck|first=Howard|title=N.B.A. Reaches a Tentative Deal to Save the Season|date=November 26, 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/27/sports/basketball/nba-and-basketball-players-reach-deal-to-end-lockout.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6DbPd7tSb|archivedate=January 11, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> According to [[CNBC]], the average player lost $220,000 after the first missed paycheck on November 15.<ref name="paychecks">{{cite news |title=For NBA players, check's not in the mail |date=November 15, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7238632/nba-lockout-average-player-loses-220000-paychecks-arrive |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63DwZkJKI |archivedate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> However, each player did receive $100,000 from the NBA to compensate for salaries falling below the 57% BRI level in 2010<U+2013>11.<ref>{{cite news |last=Washburn |first=Gary |title=This could be key checkpoint in NBA lockout |date=November 6, 2011 |newspaper=The Boston Globe |url=http://bostonglobe.com/sports/2011/11/06/with-players-about-lose-pay-this-could-key-checkpoint/PXRCOFyesAAoU3Dw2PdMpM/story.html |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63cDrT4mM |archivedate=December 1, 2011}}</ref> As of October 25, an estimated 400 NBA jobs were lost due to layoffs and attrition since the lockout<U+2014>around 200 in the league office and another 200 among the 30 teams.<ref name=beck_10262011>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=That 2011<U+2013>12 N.B.A. Schedule? Never Mind |date=October 26, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=B19 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/26/sports/basketball/nba-schedule-is-moot-as-arena-dates-are-given-up.html?_r=1&ref=sports |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62iWy81E5 |archivedate=October 26, 2011}}</ref> As the lockout dragged on toward the [[holiday season]], many NBA arenas workers felt the impact. Many of them worked part-time in order to supplement their income or to simply pay bills and they were unable to recover lost wages that resulted from cancelled games.<ref>{{cite news |last=Belson |first=Ken |title=Workers Feeling Squeezed by the N.B.A. Lockout |date=November 24, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/25/sports/basketball/in-newark-nba-lockout-costing-arena-workers-much-needed-income.html?ref=basketball |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63T7yVoDG |archivedate=November 24, 2011}}</ref>

==Players' alternatives==

===Going overseas===
The players union encouraged players to find work overseas, hoping owners would offer better deals if they saw players having more options. [[Josh Childress]], who played for Greek team [[Olympiacos B.C.|Olympiacos]] before returning to the NBA in 2010, said he would not consider playing overseas during the lockout. He cited concerns with reliability of getting paid, differences in coaching styles, and lower standards of business travel compared to the NBA.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bucher |first=Ric |authorlink=Ric Bucher |title=Perils abound when heading to Europe |date=July 12, 2011 |magazine=[[ESPN The Magazine]] |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6764023/nba-ric-bucher-perils-going-europe |accessdate=July 29, 2011}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dwyer |first=Kelly |title=Josh Childress has stern words for those looking to go overseas |date=July 13, 2011 |publisher=Yahoo! |url=http://sports.yahoo.com/nba/blog/ball_dont_lie/post/Josh-Childress-has-stern-words-for-those-looking?urn=nba-wp6375 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/60Y6lyIY3 |archivedate=July 29, 2011}}</ref> The [[FIBA|International Basketball Federation]] (FIBA) announced on July 29 that it would allow players under NBA contracts to play overseas, provided that the contracts they signed had opt-out clauses that allowed players to return once the work stoppage ended.<ref name=fiba>{{cite news |title=FIBA: NBA stars can play overseas |date=July 29, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6815642/ |accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=FIBA ruling opens global options during NBA lockout |date=July 29, 2011 |agency=[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] |publisher=Google News |url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gwK6f2zweTQzI71zoFQzsx74coxw?docId=CNG.0ada76caa7222587dc079819aa56e0a2.1191 |accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref> Stern said the league would allow players to play overseas, but he warned that it could divide the union and possibly jeopardize players' contracts if they were seriously injured.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Stern: Foreign play not 'great idea' |date=August 3, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6828492/david-stern-fan-nor-threatened-overseas-option |accessdate=August 4, 2011 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63iL9urqd |archivedate=December 5, 2011}}</ref> Most leagues permitted the signing of locked-out NBA players with the option of opting out; the [[Chinese Basketball Association]], however, only allowed its clubs to sign foreign [[free agent]]s who could play for at least the entire season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Xiaochen |first=Sun |title=New rule shuts door on NBA stars |date=August 21, 2011 |newspaper=[[China Daily]] |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/sports/2011-08/21/content_13157487.htm |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/61M9IvRBb |archivedate=August 31, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=No China for players under contract |date=August 20, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6876521/ |accessdate=September 26, 2011 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63iL1tLL2 |archivedate=December 5, 2011}}</ref> Chinese nationals were exempt from this rule; this allowed [[Yi Jianlian]] to return to the NBA upon the end of the lockout.<ref name=Wojnarowski>{{cite news|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/nba/news?slug=aw-wojnarowski_china_nba_players_112811 |title=China could block NBA players return |first=Adrian |last=Wojnarowski |work=Yahoo! Sports |date=November 29, 2011 |accessdate=November 29, 2011}}</ref>

