|colspan="5"|''For the list of all NBA players going overseas, see [[List of 2011<U+2013>12 NBA season transactions#Going overseas|2011<U+2013>12 NBA season transactions#Going overseas]].''
|}

[[List of 2011<U+2013>12 NBA season transactions#Going overseas|More than 90 players]] decided to sign with foreign teams during the lockout. ''[[The New York Times]]'' called the migration of players overseas "one of the most overblown stories of the lockout" with a majority of those signing being "rookies, middling veterans and fringe players."<ref name=beck_10132011>{{cite news |last=Bech |first=Howard |title=A Lot of Talk, but Few Stars Have Left the Country to Play |date=October 13, 2011 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/13/sports/basketball/nba-lockout-few-stars-join-foreign-teams.html?_r=1 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62Q9Biq2f |archivedate=October 13, 2011}}</ref> [[Deron Williams]] was the only [[2011 NBA All-Star Game|2011 All-Star]] going overseas, signing a one-year contract for $5 million to play for [[Be<U+015F>ikta<U+015F> men's basketball team|Be<U+015F>ikta<U+015F>]] of the [[Turkish Basketball League]].<ref name=mazzeo>{{cite news |last=Mazzeo |first=Mike |title=Deron Williams inks deal with Besiktas |date=July 15, 2011 |work=ESPNNewYork.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/nba/story/_/id/6774378/ |accessdate=July 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=beck_10132011/> Former [[List of first overall NBA draft picks|first overall draft pick]] [[Kenyon Martin]], a free agent, signed a one-year contract with the [[Xinjiang Flying Tigers]] of the Chinese Basketball Association that would make him the highest paid player in the league's history at $500,000 a month.<ref name=beck_10132011/><ref>{{cite news |last=Hochman |first=Benjamin |title=Nuggets' Kenyon Martin to sign largest contract in Chinese league's history |date=September 22, 2011 |work=The Denver Post |publisher=MediaNews Group |url=http://www.denverpost.com/nuggets/ci_18944651 |accessdate=September 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Kenyon Martin to ink Chinese league's biggest deal ever |date=September 26, 2011 |work=AOL Sporting News |publisher=Sporting News |url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/nba/feed/2011-07/nba-overseas/story/kenyon-martin-to-ink-biggest-deal-ever-in-chinese-league |accessdate=September 26, 2011}}</ref> Unlike players who signed more lucrative contracts overseas, three-time NBA champion [[Tony Parker]] opted to play for the minimum wage of $2,000 per month with [[ASVEL Basket]], the French team he partly owns.<ref name=parker>{{cite news |title=Spurs' star to play in France "nearly for free" |date=October 5, 2011 |work=CBS News |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-31751_162-20115985-10391697.html |accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tony Parker uses NBA lockout to prepare for his post-NBA future in France |date=October 6, 2011 |work=Winnipeg Free Press |publisher=Winnipeg Free Press |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/basketball/tony-parker-uses-nba-lockout-to-prepare-for-his-post-nba-future-in-france-131227014.html |accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref> Parker joined several [[List of foreign NBA players|foreign players]], such as [[Leandro Barbosa]], [[Boris Diaw]], [[Rudy Fern<U+00E1>ndez (basketball)|Rudy Fern<U+00E1>ndez]], [[Andrei Kirilenko]] and [[Mehmet Okur]], who opted to play in their home countries until the lockout ended.<ref>{{cite news |title=Player movement: Who's going abroad? |date=October 6, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6793510/ |accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref>

An NBA player playing in Europe could earn as little as $50,000<U+2013>$75,000 per month, while the average NBA annual salary was $5.8 million with the minimum around $500,000. The large contracts signed by Williams and Martin were extreme exceptions. In October after the cancellation of regular season games, it was not anticipated that many additional NBA players would be signed overseas; leagues had started playing, their rosters were full, and new players could disrupt the teams.<ref name=beck_10132011/>

===Other alternatives===
[[File:Harden & Neal Drew-Goodman.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Drew-Goodman game was one of the many exhibition basketball games played during the lockout. Here are [[James Harden (basketball)|James Harden]] (left) for the Drew League and [[Gary Neal]] (right) for the Goodman League.]]

Many players opted to stay in the United States instead. Americans especially would have found it hard to leave and change their lifestyle.<ref name=beck_10132011/> Some played in local pick-up games,<ref>{{cite news |last=Torres |first=Adry |title=Kevin Durant scores 66 at Rucker Park |date=August 2, 2011 |work=ESPNNewYork.com |url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/nba/story/_/id/6826522/ |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref> while others ranging from stars like Kevin Durant to players like [[Dorell Wright]] played in the more organized exhibition tournaments such as the Drew League in [[Los Angeles]], the Melo League located in [[Baltimore]] or the Goodman League in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Lockout added water to grass roots |date=October 10, 2011 |work=ESPNLosAngeles.com |url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/nba/story/_/id/7074191/nba-lockout-added-water-grass-roots-hoops |accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref> An exhibition game between two of the leagues was played on August 20, 2011, with the Goodman League defeating the Drew League, 135<U+2013>134.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kevin Durant, Washington win city battle |date=August 21, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6881555/ |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Drew-Goodman game lives up to hype |date=August 21, 2011 |work=ESPNLosAngeles.com |url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/nba/story/_/id/6881638/ |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref> Drew commissioner Dino Smiley said such [[pro<U+2013>am]] games during the NBA off-season were not new, but "the lockout has taken these games to a new level".<ref>{{cite news |last=Falgoust |first=J. Michael |title=NBA players stay sharp in games around the USA |date=September 20, 2011 |work=TucsonCitizen.com |publisher=[[Gannett Company]]| url=http://tucsoncitizen.com/usa-today-sports/2011/09/20/nba-players-stay-sharp-in-games-around-the-usa/ |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/61yR19H4m |archivedate=September 25, 2011}}</ref> A tournament of NBA-only players was held in September in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], featuring eight teams with seven to eight players each.<ref>{{cite news |last=Begley |first=Ian |title=Fall league set for Las Vegas |date=September 6, 2011 |work=ESPNNewYork.com |url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/nba/story/_/id/6935305/ |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref> Named the Impact Basketball Competitive Training Series, the league was dubbed by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as the "Lockout League".<ref>{{cite news |last=Bech |first=Howard |title=<U+2018>Lockout League<U+2019> Is Set to Tip Off in Las Vegas |date=September 4, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=SP11 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/04/sports/basketball/nba-lockout-league-set-to-tip-off-in-las-vegas.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=Impact%20Training%20Competitive%20Basketball%20Series&st=cse |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref>

Training camp was not expected to be long if there ended up being a season. Some players organized workouts for their teams to build team chemistry. The NBPA announced it was setting up workout centers in Las Vegas, Los Angeles, Houston and possibly Miami for players to workout at the union's expense.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson II |first=Marcus |title=Golden State Warriors ready for some serious fun |date=November 4, 2011 |newspaper=The San Jose Mercury News |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/warriors/ci_19268936 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62yQpz0LN |archivedate=November 5, 2011}}</ref>

The continuing lockout in October and the canceled preseason allowed [[Renaldo Balkman]], [[Jos<U+00E9> Juan Barea]] and [[Carlos Arroyo]] to play for [[Puerto Rico men's national basketball team|Puerto Rico]] in the [[Basketball at the 2011 Pan American Games <U+2013> Men's tournament|Pan American Games]] that month.  Puerto Rico won the gold medal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jose Juan Barea, Carlos Arroyo to play |date=October 5, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |agency=Associated Press |url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/basketball/story/_/id/7062806/jose-juan-barea-carlos-arroyo-play-puerto-rico-pan-american-games |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62DJMfy51 |archivedate=October 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Barea, Arroyo, and Balkman want to play in Pan-Am tournament |date=September 16, 2011 |work=deportesus.terra.com |publisher=Terra Networks, S.A |url=http://deportesus.terra.com/road-to-2012/noticias/0,,OI5353882-EI17467,00-Barea+Arroyo+and+Balkman+want+to+play+in+PanAm+tournament.html |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62FainFyw |archivedate=October 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wilkin |first=Tim |title=Ubiles<U+2019> agent: pro career next for Pan Am winner |date=October 31, 2011 |newspaper=[[Times Union (Albany)|Times-Union]] |url=http://blog.timesunion.com/collegesports/ubiles-agent-pro-career-next-for-pan-am-winner/11645/ |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62sdm4NzP |archivedate=November 1, 2011}}</ref>

==Outside impact==

===Olympics===
Although the [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympic men's basketball tournament]] was then more than a year away, qualifying tournaments in all five of FIBA's continental zones were to be held in the Northern Hemisphere summer of 2011 (the traditional basketball offseason throughout the world). The lockout resulted in the suspension of an agreement between the NBA and FIBA by which the NBA would take on most of the costs for insuring the value of its players' contracts in the event they were injured during international competition. As a result, national federations that wish to have NBA players on their squads must now provide full coverage instead of supplemental insurance.<ref name="Olympic fallout">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/page/Lockout-110714/nba-lockout-how-national-teams-affected-2012-games |title=London Olympics facing lockout |first=Chris |last=Sheridan |work=ESPN.com |date=July 14, 2011 |accessdate=July 27, 2011| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110717231838/http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/page/Lockout-110714/nba-lockout-how-national-teams-affected-2012-games| archivedate= July 17, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

These costs are surprisingly high<U+2014>one [[sports agent|agent]] who represents an unnamed NBA player set to earn [[United States dollar|$]]10 million in the 2010<U+2013>11 season said the player had received a $400,000 quote to insure his contract for his national team's FIBA qualifier. The [[Spanish Basketball Federation]] said that insuring all the NBA players on [[Spain national basketball team|its national team]] for [[EuroBasket 2011]], which doubles as the [[FIBA Europe|European]] Olympic qualifiers, could cost as much as $5.67 million. [[Basketball Australia]] announced that [[Andrew Bogut]] would not be available for the [[2011 FIBA Oceania Championship]]; his agent indicated that the final deal-breaker was when insurers stated that they would not insure his remaining $39 million in NBA salary unless pre-existing elbow, wrist, and back injuries were excluded from the policy.<ref name="Olympic fallout"/>

The [[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Fran<U+00E7>aise de Basket-Ball|French]], Russian and [[Argentine Basketball Federation|Argentine]] federations were able to insure their NBA players, and several other federations were also expected to be able to do so.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fiba.com/pages/eng/fc/news/lateNews/p/newsid/48230/arti.html |title=France, Russia overcome lockout insurance jam |work=[[International Basketball Federation|FIBA.com]] |date=July 22, 2011 |accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fiba.com/pages/eng/fc/news/lateNews/p/newsid/48367/arti.html |title=Argentina reach insurance deal for NBA stars |work=[[International Basketball Federation|FIBA.com]] |date=July 29, 2011 |accessdate=July 31, 2011}}</ref> Over 30 NBA players participated in [[EuroBasket 2011]], while [[Ben Gordon (basketball)|Ben Gordon]] and [[Marcin Gortat]] opted out due to insurance concerns.<ref>{{cite news |last=Zeevi |first=Elad |title=Europe's NBA stars strike out for championship |date=August 30, 2011 |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/sports/europe-s-nba-stars-strike-out-for-championship-1.381478 |accessdate=September 7, 2011 |quote=The forward is not the only one to have a revived awakening of nationalism <U+2013> over 30 NBA player will be participating in the championship which kicks off tomorrow in Lithuania.}}</ref>

===Other sports===
A couple of weeks before the NBA season was originally scheduled to start, ''[[Reuters]]'' and ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]'' speculated on the prospect of increased interest in the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) among NBA fans. The NHL had experienced steady growth since the [[2005<U+2013>06 NHL season|2005<U+2013>06 season]], and they again opened the [[2011<U+2013>12 NHL season|2011<U+2013>12 season]] in early October to record crowds. ''Businessweek'' wrote, "Just maybe, the NBA<U+2019>s sketchy situation is already having a positive effect on the NHL."<ref name=keating>{{cite news |last=Keating |first=Steve |title=NHL could have sporting spotlight as NBA lockout drags |date=October 7, 2011 |work=tvtv.com |publisher=Tanana Valley Television |url=http://tvtv.com/NHL-could-have-sporting-spotlight-as-NBA-lockout-d/7687730?newsId=105645 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62dn2tdOr |archivedate=October 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Horrow |first1=Rick |last2=Swatek |first2=Karla |title=Will NBA's Loss Be NHL's Gain? |date=October 14, 2011 |work=BusinessWeek.com |publisher=Bloomberg |url=http://www.businessweek.com/printer/lifestyle/will-nbas-loss-be-nhls-gain-10142011.html |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62dn0PRuP |archivedate=October 23, 2011}}</ref> However several NHL teams (nearly half of which do not have an NBA team in their market) had no plans to market directly to NBA fans during the lockout.<ref>{{cite news |last=Elliott |first=Helene |title=Kings, Ducks don't want to profit at NBA's expense |date=November 3, 2011 |work=Los Angeles Times |url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-nba-nhl-20111104,0,2211865.column}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Shoalts |first=David |title=Marketing business as usual for NHL? |date=November 4, 2011 |work=The Globe and Mail |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/david-shoalts/marketing-business-as-usual-for-nhl/article2226571/ |location=Toronto}}</ref>

The [[UTSA Roadrunners football|University of Texas at San Antonio]] (UTSA), in its inaugural [[college football]] [[2011 UTSA Roadrunners football team|season]], drew 40,000 fans to its games in September. The ''[[San Antonio Business Journal]]'' speculated on UTSA's opportunities to grow its fan base with the canceled NBA games in San Antonio.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baily |first=W. Scott |title=UTSA Roadrunners have benefited from NBA lockout |date=October 7, 2011 |newspaper=San Antonio Business Journal |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanantonio/print-edition/2011/10/07/utsa-roadrunners-have-benefited-from.html |accessdate=October 23, 2011}}{{subscription required}}</ref>

''[[Boston Herald]]'' speculated that [[NCAA]] [[college basketball]] would have higher television ratings and attendance during the lockout.<ref>{{cite news |last=Duggan |first=Dan |title=Colleges hope to fill void |date=October 12, 2011 |work=Boston Herald |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/college/basketball/view.bg?articleid=1372675|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62erx3vnj |archivedate=October 23, 2011}}</ref> However, ''[[Sporting News]]'' noted that "there was no obvious boost in popularity in the college game" during the [[1998<U+2013>99 NBA lockout|previous lockout]] when college basketball attendance increased by an average of 21 people per game.<ref>{{cite news |last=DeCourcy |first=Mike |title=NBA lockout will not help college hoops |date=October 21, 2011 |work=Sporting News |url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/ncaa-basketball/story/2011-10-21/nba-lockout-will-not-help-college-hoops|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/62es1tQuh|archivedate=October 23, 2011}}</ref>

===NBA cities===
Mayors from 14 NBA cities wrote an open letter to NBA commissioner [[David Stern]] and NBPA chief [[Billy Hunter (American football)|Billy Hunter]], requesting that they end the lockout based on "the perspective [of city] residents and the negative impact a canceled season might have on them, our cities, and our local economies."<ref name=gregory_11072011>{{cite news |last=Gregory |first=Sean |title=The NBA Lockout and the Economy: An Overstated Impact |date=November 7, 2011 |magazine=TIME |url=http://moneyland.time.com/2011/11/07/the-nba-lockout-and-the-economy-an-overstated-impact/ |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63DyxaDfm |archivedate=November 15, 2011}}</ref> ''[[TIME]]'' noted that arena workers would be affected by the cancellation of games. However, separate studies by [[University of Maryland, Baltimore County]] and [[Lake Forest College]] found no historic significant impact to the economies of cities with sports franchises affected by work stoppages. Explanations included consumer shifting of spending on sporting events to other forms of entertainment, reduced local government spending on crowd and traffic control, and higher productivity by the general workforce without the distraction of games.<ref name=gregory_11072011/>

===Other businesses===
It was estimated that a complete lockout had cost an upwards of $1 billion in lost television advertisement revenue. The lockout had dealt a sizable blow to the current licensed product market which was estimated at $2.7 billion, and had created a big loss in television ratings for networks that cover NBA games such as the [[regional sports network]]s, [[NBA on TNT|TNT]] and [[NBA on ESPN|ESPN]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Rich |last=Thomaselli |title=NBA Lockout Would Put $1B in TV Ad Revenue at Stake |date=January 17, 2011 |work=Advertising Age |url=http://adage.com/article/news/nba-lockout-put-1b-tv-ad-revenue-stake/148243/ |accessdate=November 25, 2011 }}</ref>

==Rescheduled season==
{{Main|2011<U+2013>12 NBA season}}
The NBA revised the schedule to play two preseason games and a 66-game regular season schedule per team rather than the standard seven preseason games and a 82-game regular season schedule.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=Two Exhibition Games for N.B.A. Teams |date=November 28, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/29/sports/basketball/two-exhibition-games-for-nba-teams.html?ref=basketball |accessdate=November 28, 2011}}</ref> Teams were allowed to contact players' agents on November 30. Players could begin working out voluntarily at team facilities with trainers on December 1, but coaches and general managers were not allowed to observe the workouts nor could any drills be conducted.<ref>{{cite news |title=Facilities, player negotiations to open |date=November 30, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/dallas/nba/story/_/id/7296919/nba-facilities-open-thursday-agents-begin-negotiate-teams-according-sources |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63axHXXyb |archivedate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> NBA teams began talking to free agents on December 5, 2011 at 10 a.m. EST.<ref>{{cite news |first=Marc |last=Stein |title=Free agents, teams can talk Monday |date=December 3, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/7311353/nba-free-agency-courting-start-monday-sources-say |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63fUiicce |archivedate=December 3, 2011}}</ref> Training camps and free agency started on December 9 with the regular season beginning on [[National Basketball Association Christmas games|Christmas Day]] with five games, two more than the original schedule.<ref name="tentativedeal"/><ref name="OpeningDay">{{cite news|title=Magic-Thunder, Clippers-Warriors set for Christmas|date=December 2, 2011|accessdate=December 3, 2011|first=Brian|last=Mahoney|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> [[NBA on ESPN|ESPN]]/[[NBA on ABC|ABC]] analyst [[Jeff Van Gundy]] said about the NBA opening on Christmas Day: "It's a different opening day than has ever happened in the past and Christmas Day games have always been a big day for the NBA. This unique situation combined with the unveiling of a championship banner for the Mavericks in a finals rematch, and then to see the Lakers and the debut of Mike Brown as head coach, those things are all going to be very compelling."<ref name="OpeningDay"/>

The league built a new schedule from scratch based on available arena dates.  In October, the league had allowed arenas in [[Staples Center|Los Angeles]] and [[United Center|Chicago]] to reassign NBA dates for other events. The number of games between conferences was affected as was the case in the 1999 lockout, when each team played only five or six interconference games in a 50-game schedule.  Normally, each team plays teams in the other conference twice each.<ref name=beck_10262011/> Teams played 48&nbsp;conference games and 18&nbsp;non-conference games in a 66-game schedule, compared to 52&nbsp;conference games and 30&nbsp;non-conference games in a normal 82-game season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Banks |first=Lacy J. |title=NBA<U+2019>s 66-game schedule is definitely hectic |date=November 27, 2011 |newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times |url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/basketball/bulls/9102076-579/nbas-66-game-schedule-is-definitely-hectic.html |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63gZFSLVD |archivedate=December 4, 2011}}</ref> Teams played on average two more games per month and also played three-consecutive games at least once in the season. In total, the league had 42&nbsp;sets of back-to-back-to-back games, with 11&nbsp;teams playing two such sets.<ref name=66games/><ref name=howard_12072011/><ref name=borzi>{{cite news |last=Borzi |first=Pat |title=No Rest (but Four Wins) for the Weary Bulls |date=January 13, 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=B9 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/13/sports/basketball/nbas-bulls-survive-five-games-in-six-nights.html?pagewanted=all |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/64lrONGAa |archivedate=January 17, 2012}}</ref> The three-game set, or "triple", had not occurred since the shortened 1999 season, which featured 64&nbsp;triples and sloppier play due to tired players.<ref name=66games>{{cite news |title=NBA announces shortened 66-game schedule |date=December 6, 2011 |publisher=CBS Sports |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nba/story/16352433/nba-announces-shortened-66game-schedule}}</ref><ref name=howard_12072011>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Howard |title=N.B.A. Schedule a Cram Course for Teams |date=December 7, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=B12 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/07/sports/basketball/nba-schedule-a-cram-course-for-teams.html |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63mfFYMHA |archivedate=December 8, 2011}}</ref> Before that, the last occurrence was two decades earlier.<ref name=howard_12072011/> During the season, there were 29 occasions when teams played five games in six days.<ref name=borzi/> 

With fewer off days during the season, the level of play was lower due to fatigue, and some older players rested to avoid burnout and recuperate from injuries.<ref>{{cite news|last=Haper|first=Jake|title=Boston Celtics coach Doc Rivers, LA Clippers star Blake Griffin discuss impact of shortened NBA season|date=April 28, 2012|work=foxsports.com.au|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/other-sports/basketball/boston-celtics-coach-doc-rivers-la-clippers-star-blake-griffin-discuss-impact-of-shortened-nba-season/story-e6frf3f3-1226341578871#.UPC8Aqx8N8E|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6DbYd0QR2|archivedate=January 11, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> When the [[2011<U+2013>12 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio Spurs]] rested [[Tim Duncan]] for a game in March at the end of a back-to-back-to-back, coach [[Gregg Popovich]] submitted the description of Duncan's absence as "Old".<ref>{{cite news|last=Dwyer|first=Kelly|title=Tim Duncan missed Sunday night<U+2019>s Spurs game because he<U+2019>s <U+2018>old,<U+2019> officially|date=March 26, 2012|work=yahoo.com|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nba-ball-dont-lie/tim-duncan-missed-sunday-night-spurs-game-because-081218158.html|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Dbb85Owm|archivedate=January 11, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> Nonetheless, some players still sustained injuries. In the [[2012 NBA Playoffs|2012 playoffs]], the [[2011<U+2013>12 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago Bulls]] were eliminated after losing [[Derrick Rose]] and [[Joakim Noah]] to injuries, and the [[2011<U+2013>12 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]] lost to the [[2011<U+2013>12 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]] while losing [[Baron Davis]] and [[Iman Shumpert]] to knee injuries.  The Heat were not immune, losing [[Chris Bosh]] for most of the playoffs en route to their NBA championship. Stern initially said there was no connection between the injuries and the 66-game schedule compressed into 124 days; however, he backed off those comments a week later, saying more research was needed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zillgitt|first=Jeff|title=NBA deals with postseason trauma as stars go down|date=May 15, 2012|newspaper=USA Today|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/story/2012-05-14/NBA-playoff-trauma-with-Derrick-Rose-Chris-Bosh-injuries/54964494/1|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6DbTXijhm|archivedate=January 11, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Stern suggests shortened training camp may be reason for injury trend|date=May 9, 2012|work=SportingNews.com|url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/nba/story/2012-05-09/baron-davis-dwight-howard-derrick-rose-injury-david-stern-nba-playoffs-injuries|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6DbTqktI2|archivedate=January 11, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref>

